1
00:00:07,007 --> 00:00:10,488
[MUSIC PLAYING]

2
00:02:06,778 --> 00:02:08,824
[MUSIC PLAYING]

3
00:02:08,867 --> 00:02:12,784
[SINGING ON RADIO] Heaven, how
you danced before.

4
00:02:12,828 --> 00:02:16,266
Heaven when you eyes meet mine.

5
00:02:16,310 --> 00:02:19,791
[BALL BOUNCING]

6
00:02:19,835 --> 00:02:21,010
[FAINT LAUGHTER]

7
00:02:21,053 --> 00:02:23,230
[SINGING] Charm everyone that
you meet.

8
00:02:23,273 --> 00:02:25,232
[FOREBODING MUSIC]

9
00:02:25,275 --> 00:02:28,757
[MUTTERING]

10
00:02:28,800 --> 00:02:29,888
MAN: I want to see my daughter.

11
00:02:29,932 --> 00:02:31,238
I want to see her now.

12
00:02:31,281 --> 00:02:32,282
You gotta come in now.

13
00:02:35,111 --> 00:02:36,199
ATTENDANT: Here you go,
sweetheart.

14
00:02:36,243 --> 00:02:39,202
You take these now.

15
00:02:39,246 --> 00:02:40,203
[FAINT LAUGHTER]

16
00:02:40,247 --> 00:02:41,204
CHILD: Busted!

17
00:02:41,248 --> 00:02:44,207
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

18
00:02:44,251 --> 00:02:45,339
[BANGING]

19
00:02:46,253 --> 00:02:49,691
[DRUMMING]

20
00:02:49,734 --> 00:02:52,737
[FOREBODING MUSIC]

21
00:02:57,742 --> 00:02:59,701
ATTENDANT [ON LOUDSPEAKER]: If
Dr. Smith is in the building,

22
00:02:59,744 --> 00:03:02,225
will you please report to Nurse
[INAUDIBLE]..

23
00:03:21,201 --> 00:03:22,245
[DOOR OPENS]

24
00:03:23,203 --> 00:03:24,204
[DOOR CLOSES]

25
00:03:58,150 --> 00:04:01,589
[WHIMPERING]

26
00:04:14,079 --> 00:04:15,516
[SCREAMING]

27
00:04:15,559 --> 00:04:17,561
[BANGING ON WINDOW]

28
00:04:26,178 --> 00:04:27,005
Nurse!

29
00:04:27,049 --> 00:04:28,485
Help!

30
00:04:28,529 --> 00:04:30,008
Nurse, nurse!

31
00:04:30,052 --> 00:04:32,010
Somebody help me!

32
00:04:32,054 --> 00:04:33,055
Somebody help!

33
00:04:35,623 --> 00:04:36,537
Hurry!

34
00:04:47,504 --> 00:04:51,029
[MUSIC PLAYING]

35
00:05:02,258 --> 00:05:04,216
DENISE WILCOX [VOICEOVER]:
Journalism 101,

36
00:05:04,260 --> 00:05:08,046
the lead paragraph in any story
should answer the five W's--

37
00:05:08,090 --> 00:05:12,007
who, what, where, when, and,
finally, why.

38
00:05:12,050 --> 00:05:13,225
Who?

39
00:05:13,269 --> 00:05:16,098
Denise Wilcox, that would be me.

40
00:05:16,141 --> 00:05:17,099
What?

41
00:05:17,142 --> 00:05:19,623
Writing the obituary column.

42
00:05:19,667 --> 00:05:20,668
Where?

43
00:05:20,711 --> 00:05:22,670
In "The Tribune" Newspaper
Building

44
00:05:22,713 --> 00:05:25,934
or, to be more precise, in the
morgue of "The Tribune"

45
00:05:25,977 --> 00:05:28,632
Newspaper Building, the place
where

46
00:05:28,676 --> 00:05:31,113
all dead files come to rest.

47
00:05:31,156 --> 00:05:32,375
When?

48
00:05:32,419 --> 00:05:35,247
16 hours a day, six days a week.

49
00:05:35,291 --> 00:05:36,161
Why?

50
00:05:36,205 --> 00:05:37,293
[PHONE RINGING]

51
00:05:37,337 --> 00:05:40,209
Because it's an important public
service.

52
00:05:40,252 --> 00:05:43,081
Hello, this is Denise Wilcox
with "The Tribune."

53
00:05:43,125 --> 00:05:44,692
Is this Mr. Harold Johnson?

54
00:05:44,735 --> 00:05:46,520
HAROLD JOHNSON [ON PHONE]: Yes,
it is.

55
00:05:46,563 --> 00:05:49,305
I'm sorry for your loss, Mr.
Johnson.

56
00:05:49,349 --> 00:05:52,569
I would like to confirm a few
details of your wife's death.

57
00:05:52,613 --> 00:05:54,005
DENISE WILCOX [VOICEOVER]: Why?

58
00:05:54,049 --> 00:05:55,833
Because everyone deserves an
accurate

59
00:05:55,877 --> 00:05:57,226
reflection of their life.

60
00:05:57,269 --> 00:05:58,183
Thank you.

61
00:05:58,227 --> 00:05:59,489
All right.

62
00:05:59,533 --> 00:06:01,491
Got "The Trib" copies on top,
both the papers

63
00:06:01,535 --> 00:06:04,146
next, then the out of towns.

64
00:06:04,189 --> 00:06:05,756
[SIGH] Did you pull another all
nighter?

65
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:08,150
Yep.

66
00:06:08,193 --> 00:06:09,238
Maybe, when you're finished, do

67
00:06:09,281 --> 00:06:11,066
you want to go, uh, for a bite?

68
00:06:11,109 --> 00:06:11,980
No, thanks.

69
00:06:12,023 --> 00:06:13,416
I'm swamped.

70
00:06:13,460 --> 00:06:15,592
You know, I do not know why you
work so hard.

71
00:06:15,636 --> 00:06:17,159
It's just an obituary column.

72
00:06:17,202 --> 00:06:19,074
Opinion noted.

73
00:06:19,117 --> 00:06:20,118
DENISE WILCOX [VOICEOVER]: Why?

74
00:06:20,162 --> 00:06:22,469
Because Stanley Morgan is old.

75
00:06:22,512 --> 00:06:25,080
Because he pushes himself too
hard.

76
00:06:25,123 --> 00:06:27,691
Because he smokes two packs a
day.

77
00:06:27,735 --> 00:06:30,302
Because he thinks a square meal
is a club sandwich.

78
00:06:30,346 --> 00:06:31,434
[CHOKING]

79
00:06:31,478 --> 00:06:33,436
And because it's only a matter
of time.

80
00:06:33,480 --> 00:06:35,177
[GRIMACING IN PAIN]

81
00:06:35,220 --> 00:06:37,048
And because I desperately want
his job.

82
00:06:37,092 --> 00:06:38,136
[THUMP]

83
00:06:38,180 --> 00:06:39,050
[THUMP]

84
00:06:39,094 --> 00:06:42,532
[MUSIC PLAYING]

85
00:06:43,533 --> 00:06:46,014
[TINKING]

86
00:06:46,057 --> 00:06:47,537
[MECHANICAL SQUEAKING]

87
00:06:50,497 --> 00:06:51,498
[GASP]

88
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:58,940
OPERATOR [ON PHONE]: 911.

89
00:06:58,983 --> 00:07:13,389
[DRAWER SLAMS]

90
00:07:13,433 --> 00:07:14,303
Excuse me.

91
00:07:17,306 --> 00:07:18,916
DENISE WILCOX [VOICEOVER]:
Dedicated news reporter

92
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:22,572
for "The Tribune," longtime
social activist,

93
00:07:22,616 --> 00:07:27,011
honored many times by the city
service, organizations.

94
00:07:27,055 --> 00:07:27,882
[STEADY BEEP]

95
00:07:27,925 --> 00:07:28,970
Clear.

96
00:07:29,013 --> 00:07:29,840
[ZAP]

97
00:07:29,884 --> 00:07:30,841
[BEEPING]

98
00:07:30,885 --> 00:07:32,756
[STEADY BEEP]

99
00:07:32,800 --> 00:07:34,758
[ELECTRICAL CHARGING]

100
00:07:34,802 --> 00:07:36,499
Do it again.

101
00:07:36,543 --> 00:07:37,848
Clear.

102
00:07:37,892 --> 00:07:39,067
[GASP]

103
00:07:39,110 --> 00:07:42,374
Survived by his wife and two
children.

104
00:07:42,418 --> 00:07:43,288
[BEEPING]

105
00:07:43,332 --> 00:07:46,291
Get those, people.

106
00:07:46,335 --> 00:07:47,205
[STEADY BEEP]

107
00:07:47,249 --> 00:07:48,685
Take him around, please.

108
00:07:53,124 --> 00:07:54,517
[PHONE RINGING]

109
00:07:54,561 --> 00:07:55,649
Denise Wilcox.

110
00:07:55,692 --> 00:07:56,824
MISS KIRKWOOD [ON PHONE]: Miss
Wilcox,

111
00:07:56,867 --> 00:07:58,478
this is Miss Kirkwood at City
West

112
00:07:58,521 --> 00:08:00,305
Hospital returning your call.

113
00:08:00,349 --> 00:08:03,395
Sorry for the delay, but the EMT
report just came in.

114
00:08:03,439 --> 00:08:06,181
Mr. Morgan's time of death was
6:45 PM.

115
00:08:06,224 --> 00:08:07,095
Thank you.

116
00:08:07,138 --> 00:08:08,052
[HANGS UP]

117
00:08:08,096 --> 00:08:10,011
[TYPING]

118
00:08:10,054 --> 00:08:11,055
[BEEP]

119
00:08:15,495 --> 00:08:20,717
You were one heck of a reporter,
Stanley, a real pro.

120
00:08:23,677 --> 00:08:24,678
[CAR DOOR OPENS]

121
00:08:27,637 --> 00:08:28,638
[CAR DOOR SLAMS]

122
00:08:36,080 --> 00:08:39,519
[EXOTIC MUSIC PLAYING]

123
00:08:49,441 --> 00:08:52,880
[BELL JINGLES]

124
00:08:52,923 --> 00:08:55,186
Ah, Miss Denise.

125
00:08:55,230 --> 00:08:56,274
Hey, Mr. Lee.

126
00:08:56,318 --> 00:08:57,232
Just one moment, huh?

127
00:08:57,275 --> 00:08:58,189
OK.

128
00:09:10,941 --> 00:09:17,165
Here, Miss Denise, one regular.

129
00:09:17,208 --> 00:09:19,254
You should find nice man.

130
00:09:19,297 --> 00:09:23,040
Take you out for dinner instead
of always chicken chow mein.

131
00:09:23,084 --> 00:09:24,564
I know.

132
00:09:24,607 --> 00:09:30,831
Here, for you, for good luck,
eh?

133
00:09:30,874 --> 00:09:32,354
Thank you.

134
00:09:32,397 --> 00:09:35,444
[BIRDSONG]

135
00:09:36,358 --> 00:09:38,752
[CAR DOOR OPENS]

136
00:09:38,795 --> 00:09:39,753
[CAR DOOR SLAMS]

137
00:09:53,636 --> 00:09:54,898
[BEEP]

138
00:09:54,942 --> 00:09:56,204
ANSWERING MACHINE: You have no
new messages.

139
00:09:56,247 --> 00:09:59,686
[MUSIC PLAYING]

140
00:10:18,139 --> 00:10:19,053
[SIGH]

141
00:10:19,575 --> 00:10:20,445
Perfect.

142
00:10:31,239 --> 00:10:33,633
Hey there, Lizzie, how was your
day?

143
00:10:37,201 --> 00:10:39,377
You hungry?

144
00:10:39,421 --> 00:10:40,335
No?

145
00:10:45,819 --> 00:10:46,733
[CHIRP]

146
00:10:51,172 --> 00:10:53,653
Stanley was from the old
school.

147
00:10:53,696 --> 00:10:57,744
He-- he knew the meaning of the
words tenacity,

148
00:10:57,787 --> 00:11:00,572
integrity, dedication.

149
00:11:00,616 --> 00:11:03,967
So here's to one heck of a
reporter.

150
00:11:04,011 --> 00:11:07,971
It was a pleasure to be your
editor and your friend.

151
00:11:08,015 --> 00:11:10,887
To Stanley, we will miss you.

152
00:11:10,931 --> 00:11:12,584
But we will never forget you.

153
00:11:12,628 --> 00:11:13,629
ALL: To Stanley.

154
00:11:19,635 --> 00:11:23,073
[CROWD MURMURING]

155
00:11:25,075 --> 00:11:26,555
Hey.

156
00:11:26,598 --> 00:11:27,948
It was nice of you to let
Stanley's family

157
00:11:27,991 --> 00:11:29,471
use the paper for the service.

158
00:11:29,514 --> 00:11:31,821
Oh, he spent most of his life
in this building.

159
00:11:31,865 --> 00:11:32,996
It only seemed appropriate.

160
00:11:33,040 --> 00:11:34,258
Yeah.

161
00:11:34,302 --> 00:11:35,477
I was wondering if you had a
chance to look

162
00:11:35,520 --> 00:11:38,262
at my resume and sample pieces.
- When?

163
00:11:38,306 --> 00:11:39,873
Yeah, I put them on your desk
in an envelope

164
00:11:39,916 --> 00:11:41,048
marked important.

165
00:11:41,091 --> 00:11:43,224
This is not the time nor the
place.

166
00:11:43,267 --> 00:11:44,355
I'm sorry.

167
00:11:44,399 --> 00:11:45,530
I came to your office several
times.

168
00:11:45,574 --> 00:11:46,618
But you were always busy.

169
00:11:46,662 --> 00:11:47,750
Excuse me.

170
00:11:47,794 --> 00:11:48,751
Simon.

171
00:11:48,795 --> 00:11:49,709
SIMON: Good to see you, Rog.

172
00:11:49,752 --> 00:11:53,060
[MUSIC PLAYING]

173
00:11:55,889 --> 00:11:56,803
Simon.

174
00:11:56,846 --> 00:11:59,719
Denny, hi.

175
00:11:59,762 --> 00:12:01,111
You knew Stanley?

176
00:12:01,155 --> 00:12:03,505
I met him at a conference last
summer.

177
00:12:03,548 --> 00:12:04,941
Oh.

178
00:12:04,985 --> 00:12:06,595
- You look good. - Yeah.

179
00:12:06,638 --> 00:12:07,509
Yeah, right.

180
00:12:07,552 --> 00:12:09,598
Black's my color.

181
00:12:09,641 --> 00:12:11,556
You, come.

182
00:12:11,600 --> 00:12:13,080
Hey, I've got to go.

183
00:12:22,045 --> 00:12:25,527
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

184
00:12:27,007 --> 00:12:30,488
[MUSIC PLAYING]

185
00:12:30,532 --> 00:12:31,489
[SWOOSH]

186
00:12:31,533 --> 00:12:32,490
Oh, Denny.

187
00:12:32,534 --> 00:12:34,579
[HEAVY BREATHING]

188
00:12:34,623 --> 00:12:35,493
Mm.

189
00:12:38,975 --> 00:12:40,455
Simon.

190
00:12:40,498 --> 00:12:41,412
[DOOR OPENING]

191
00:12:41,456 --> 00:12:44,938
[BIRDSONG]

192
00:12:48,942 --> 00:12:52,423
[MUSIC PLAYING]

193
00:13:04,958 --> 00:13:05,828
[THUMP]

194
00:13:05,872 --> 00:13:06,786
Uh!

195
00:13:50,742 --> 00:13:51,613
How's your head?

196
00:13:54,964 --> 00:13:56,139
I found a body.

197
00:13:56,183 --> 00:13:58,141
There's been a murder.

198
00:13:58,185 --> 00:13:59,012
Yeah.

199
00:13:59,055 --> 00:14:00,013
You able to talk to me?

200
00:14:00,056 --> 00:14:01,144
I got to get a statement.

201
00:14:01,188 --> 00:14:02,189
Yeah, yeah.

202
00:14:02,232 --> 00:14:04,365
Denise Wilcox, with "The
Tribune."

203
00:14:04,408 --> 00:14:06,584
Walker, there's something you
need to see.

204
00:14:06,628 --> 00:14:07,455
Wait here.

205
00:14:07,498 --> 00:14:10,458
I'll be right back.

206
00:14:10,501 --> 00:14:12,808
Do you have an ID on the body?

207
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:14,679
What about the time of death?

208
00:14:14,723 --> 00:14:17,378
Miss Wilcox, I ask the
questions around here.

209
00:14:17,421 --> 00:14:18,422
Why don't you put that away?

210
00:14:21,251 --> 00:14:23,427
Denny.

211
00:14:23,471 --> 00:14:25,168
Listen, I heard what happened.

212
00:14:25,212 --> 00:14:26,517
Are you all right?

213
00:14:26,561 --> 00:14:27,692
What are you doing here?

214
00:14:27,736 --> 00:14:29,738
I'm with "The Tribune."

215
00:14:29,781 --> 00:14:31,392
You're taking over city news?

216
00:14:31,435 --> 00:14:33,437
Well, Stanley kind of
recommended me.

217
00:14:33,481 --> 00:14:35,396
You got to be kidding me.

218
00:14:35,439 --> 00:14:36,310
Wow.

219
00:14:36,353 --> 00:14:37,180
This is awkward.

220
00:14:37,224 --> 00:14:38,747
I was in line for that job.

221
00:14:38,790 --> 00:14:40,662
We're ready for your statement.

222
00:14:40,705 --> 00:14:42,359
Listen, if there's anything I
can do.

223
00:14:42,403 --> 00:14:43,578
Yeah.

224
00:14:43,621 --> 00:14:45,406
You can find the nearest bridge
and jump.

225
00:14:45,449 --> 00:14:48,496
Well, it's good to see you
haven't changed at all, Denny.

226
00:14:48,539 --> 00:14:50,106
Stop calling me that.

227
00:14:50,150 --> 00:14:51,716
No one's called me that since
high school.

228
00:14:54,589 --> 00:14:58,071
There was a man coming from the
direction of the body.

229
00:14:58,114 --> 00:15:00,595
He ran past me and bumped my
arm.

230
00:15:00,638 --> 00:15:02,031
What was he wearing?

231
00:15:02,075 --> 00:15:03,772
I-- I couldn't really see him.

232
00:15:03,815 --> 00:15:05,687
He-- he was-- had black on.

233
00:15:05,730 --> 00:15:07,341
He had a hood on.

234
00:15:07,384 --> 00:15:08,646
OK.

235
00:15:08,690 --> 00:15:12,346
You have no idea what color his
shoes were.

236
00:15:12,389 --> 00:15:13,956
You don't know what he looked
like.

237
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:16,089
And you have no idea whether or
not you saw any blood there.

238
00:15:16,132 --> 00:15:17,003
It's funny.

239
00:15:17,046 --> 00:15:18,482
You're a wannabe reporter.

240
00:15:18,526 --> 00:15:21,094
And all you can tell me is that
the guy had a hood on.

241
00:15:21,137 --> 00:15:22,269
I don't get it.

242
00:15:22,312 --> 00:15:24,401
You go for a jog at the crack of
dawn.

243
00:15:24,445 --> 00:15:25,707
You trip over a dead body.

244
00:15:25,750 --> 00:15:27,143
And the first thing you do when
you come to

245
00:15:27,187 --> 00:15:28,231
is you pull out that thing.

246
00:15:28,275 --> 00:15:30,364
You start jotting down notes.

247
00:15:30,407 --> 00:15:33,758
Do you always carry that thing
with you when you go jogging?

248
00:15:33,802 --> 00:15:35,978
Well, I'm a wannabe reporter.

249
00:15:36,022 --> 00:15:37,980
We tend to do those kinds of
things.

250
00:15:38,024 --> 00:15:40,635
What were you doing in Ramsey
Park?

251
00:15:40,678 --> 00:15:41,853
I jog here all the time.

252
00:15:41,897 --> 00:15:43,420
It's my regular route.

253
00:15:43,464 --> 00:15:44,987
Alone?

254
00:15:45,031 --> 00:15:46,946
Are you going to check out the
guy with the hood or not?

255
00:15:46,989 --> 00:15:47,947
Yeah, we will.

256
00:15:51,167 --> 00:15:53,735
Is there anything else you want
to tell us?

257
00:15:53,778 --> 00:15:54,823
No.

258
00:15:54,866 --> 00:15:55,737
That's it.

259
00:15:55,780 --> 00:15:56,651
That's all I can remember.

260
00:16:03,310 --> 00:16:05,616
Did you even look at the
envelope I put on your desk?

261
00:16:05,660 --> 00:16:07,270
I wrote over a dozen spec
pieces--

262
00:16:07,314 --> 00:16:08,968
a human interest story, an
opinion--

263
00:16:09,011 --> 00:16:11,883
It's probably in there
somewhere.

264
00:16:11,927 --> 00:16:13,755
You could have at least given
it due consideration.

265
00:16:13,798 --> 00:16:16,192
Instead Simon just waltzes in
here?

266
00:16:16,236 --> 00:16:18,020
Simon is extremely well
qualified.

267
00:16:18,064 --> 00:16:21,328
He has a master's in journalism
from Champlain College, not

268
00:16:21,371 --> 00:16:24,157
to mention years of solid work
experience

269
00:16:24,200 --> 00:16:25,897
at two different newspapers. -
OK.

270
00:16:25,941 --> 00:16:27,856
So the fact that I've worked my
butt off for the past three

271
00:16:27,899 --> 00:16:30,815
years doesn't mean a thing?

272
00:16:30,859 --> 00:16:35,037
