816
00:44:46,684 --> 00:44:47,597
[SIGH]

817
00:44:47,641 --> 00:44:50,383
[CHIMING]

818
00:44:50,426 --> 00:44:52,167
COMPUTER: Click here. Click
here.

819
00:44:52,211 --> 00:44:53,125
Click here.

820
00:44:53,168 --> 00:44:56,650
[MUSIC PLAYING]

821
00:45:12,927 --> 00:45:13,928
[CAR DOOR OPENS]

822
00:45:16,409 --> 00:45:17,366
[CAR DOOR SLAMS]

823
00:45:19,847 --> 00:45:21,327
[DOG BARKING]

824
00:45:29,814 --> 00:45:31,685
[KNOCKING]

825
00:45:34,079 --> 00:45:36,646
Hi, I'm looking for a Mr.
Foster.

826
00:45:36,690 --> 00:45:38,083
He's listed as living here in
the phone book,

827
00:45:38,126 --> 00:45:39,388
but he may have moved.

828
00:45:39,432 --> 00:45:41,651
I'm Mr. Foster

829
00:45:41,695 --> 00:45:43,131
Is your first initial C?

830
00:45:43,175 --> 00:45:44,611
No, Ivan.

831
00:45:44,654 --> 00:45:46,134
There's a C. Foster at this
address.

832
00:45:50,138 --> 00:45:50,965
I'm too late.

833
00:45:51,009 --> 00:45:52,097
I'm sorry.

834
00:45:52,140 --> 00:45:53,620
He was killed two weeks ago.

835
00:45:53,663 --> 00:45:56,405
We just got his body back
yesterday.

836
00:45:56,449 --> 00:45:58,190
I'm a reporter with "The
Tribune."

837
00:45:58,233 --> 00:46:00,714
Do you mind if I ask you a few
questions?

838
00:46:00,758 --> 00:46:02,281
Sir, was he strangled?

839
00:46:02,324 --> 00:46:04,109
Strangled?

840
00:46:04,152 --> 00:46:06,938
It was a roadside bomb, same as
most of them.

841
00:46:06,981 --> 00:46:08,591
What do you mean, most of them?

842
00:46:08,635 --> 00:46:10,811
The boys in Iraq.

843
00:46:10,855 --> 00:46:12,726
What the heck do you think I
mean?

844
00:46:12,770 --> 00:46:16,469
Was there a yellow scarf with
his body?

845
00:46:16,512 --> 00:46:18,601
What are you talking about?

846
00:46:18,645 --> 00:46:21,822
Maybe there was a yellow scarf
with the body or a yellow

847
00:46:21,866 --> 00:46:22,910
ribbon, like-- like a medal.

848
00:46:22,954 --> 00:46:24,694
Or maybe you wore a yellow
ribbon.

849
00:46:24,738 --> 00:46:27,567
What would I wear a yellow
ribbon for?

850
00:46:27,610 --> 00:46:29,612
Because you were waiting for a
loved one to return from war.

851
00:46:29,656 --> 00:46:31,614
What? Are you crazy?

852
00:46:31,658 --> 00:46:34,356
I don't know anything about
yellow ribbons.

853
00:46:34,400 --> 00:46:36,097
Just leave me alone.

854
00:46:36,141 --> 00:46:37,055
[DOOR CLOSES]

855
00:46:37,098 --> 00:46:40,623
[MUSIC PLAYING]

856
00:46:49,589 --> 00:46:53,071
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO]

857
00:46:55,682 --> 00:46:56,509
[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

858
00:46:56,552 --> 00:46:59,512
[DRILLING]

859
00:46:59,555 --> 00:47:00,905
Excuse me, sir.

860
00:47:00,948 --> 00:47:01,862
Hi.

861
00:47:01,906 --> 00:47:02,863
Just a sec.

862
00:47:02,907 --> 00:47:04,778
[DRILLING]

863
00:47:06,127 --> 00:47:07,520
That your car?

864
00:47:07,563 --> 00:47:09,043
Yeah, I'm not here about my
car.

865
00:47:09,087 --> 00:47:11,089
I'm looking for someone.

866
00:47:11,132 --> 00:47:12,351
He ain't here.

867
00:47:12,394 --> 00:47:14,527
I haven't told you who I'm
looking for.

868
00:47:14,570 --> 00:47:16,224
Yeah, well, we're a garage.

869
00:47:16,268 --> 00:47:17,835
You know, if you're collection
agency

870
00:47:17,878 --> 00:47:20,533
looking for support payments or
alimony or whatever,

871
00:47:20,576 --> 00:47:21,621
he ain't here.

872
00:47:21,664 --> 00:47:23,057
Please, I need to find Carl
Foster.

873
00:47:30,195 --> 00:47:32,893
And what would you be needing
Carl for?

874
00:47:32,937 --> 00:47:34,329
I'm with "The Tribune."

875
00:47:34,373 --> 00:47:37,376
It's important that I talk to
him.

876
00:47:37,419 --> 00:47:38,507
That's a good one.

877
00:47:38,551 --> 00:47:41,075
[LAUGHTER] Did Kenny put you up
to this?

878
00:47:41,119 --> 00:47:41,946
No.

879
00:47:41,989 --> 00:47:43,338
I--

880
00:47:43,382 --> 00:47:46,515
Because you almost had me going
there-- for a sec.

881
00:47:46,559 --> 00:47:47,821
Carl Foster.

882
00:47:47,865 --> 00:47:49,867
Hey Carl, there's a lady looking
for you here.

883
00:47:49,910 --> 00:47:53,305
[DOG BARKING]

884
00:47:53,348 --> 00:47:56,786
[LAUGHTER]

885
00:47:56,830 --> 00:48:06,884
[DOG BARKS]

886
00:48:06,884 --> 00:48:15,109
[DOG BARKS]

887
00:48:15,153 --> 00:48:17,155
The morning Melissa Rutherford
was killed,

888
00:48:17,198 --> 00:48:19,418
I saw her obituary in a Chinese
newspaper.

889
00:48:19,461 --> 00:48:20,810
I have no idea how it got there.

890
00:48:20,854 --> 00:48:23,030
When I went back to look, it was
an advertisement.

891
00:48:23,074 --> 00:48:25,380
And then Lorna Woods, I saw her
obituary on my computer

892
00:48:25,424 --> 00:48:27,252
the morning before she died. And
I tried to tell her.

893
00:48:27,295 --> 00:48:28,818
And she wouldn't listen.

894
00:48:28,862 --> 00:48:31,299
So when I got something for Carl
Foster, I had to warn him

895
00:48:31,343 --> 00:48:32,953
or I'd never be able to live
with myself.

896
00:48:32,997 --> 00:48:34,999
So you tracked down a dog.

897
00:48:35,042 --> 00:48:36,261
Oh, Ivan Foster called.

898
00:48:36,304 --> 00:48:38,002
You thought you were crazy and
dangerous.

899
00:48:38,045 --> 00:48:38,959
I'm sorry.

900
00:48:39,003 --> 00:48:40,091
I'm sorry.

901
00:48:40,134 --> 00:48:41,396
You said research only.

902
00:48:41,440 --> 00:48:43,485
You said you wouldn't involve
the newspaper.

903
00:48:43,529 --> 00:48:45,270
And here you go, traipsing all
over town,

904
00:48:45,313 --> 00:48:46,706
dragging our name through the
mud.

905
00:48:46,749 --> 00:48:49,013
And not only that, you've been
neglecting your job.

906
00:48:49,056 --> 00:48:53,626
I've got here, what, four
complaints

907
00:48:53,669 --> 00:48:55,628
about the obituaries.

908
00:48:55,671 --> 00:48:58,283
Denise, what's going on?

909
00:48:58,326 --> 00:48:59,980
I have no idea.

910
00:49:00,024 --> 00:49:02,026
You've become so obsessed with
death.

911
00:49:02,069 --> 00:49:04,550
You're seeing things that aren't
there.

912
00:49:04,593 --> 00:49:05,899
What are you saying?

913
00:49:05,943 --> 00:49:07,857
You need to take some time off.

914
00:49:07,901 --> 00:49:08,728
No.

915
00:49:08,771 --> 00:49:09,947
I'm fine.

916
00:49:09,990 --> 00:49:11,600
It's not a suggestion.

917
00:49:11,644 --> 00:49:13,951
What?

918
00:49:13,994 --> 00:49:15,256
You're firing me?

919
00:49:15,300 --> 00:49:16,127
I've been fair.

920
00:49:16,170 --> 00:49:17,345
I've cut you slack.

921
00:49:17,389 --> 00:49:18,912
I've even had you see Dr.
Greenberg.

922
00:49:18,956 --> 00:49:21,741
But enough is enough.

923
00:49:21,784 --> 00:49:24,526
Oh, for the record, I had Simon
check out

924
00:49:24,570 --> 00:49:26,920
that little theory of yours.

925
00:49:26,964 --> 00:49:27,965
Simon?

926
00:49:28,008 --> 00:49:30,010
Lorna did have a tattoo.

927
00:49:30,054 --> 00:49:31,316
But it wasn't some cult thing.

928
00:49:31,359 --> 00:49:33,361
Her mother said it was a warrior
woman symbol.

929
00:49:33,405 --> 00:49:35,450
She had just gotten out of an
abusive relationship.

930
00:49:35,494 --> 00:49:38,758
And it was her way of, uh,
reclaiming her feminine power.

931
00:49:38,801 --> 00:49:40,238
But it's still Kali.

932
00:49:40,281 --> 00:49:41,804
Not to Lorna it wasn't.

933
00:49:41,848 --> 00:49:44,416
The point is she wasn't a
Thuggee like you seem to think.

934
00:49:44,459 --> 00:49:46,896
What about the graffiti near
Ramsey Park?

935
00:49:46,940 --> 00:49:48,594
It was a clown picture.

936
00:49:48,637 --> 00:49:52,250
No, that's impossible.

937
00:49:52,293 --> 00:49:55,818
[MUSIC PLAYING]

938
00:49:57,255 --> 00:49:59,953
Now could you please get out of
my office?

939
00:49:59,997 --> 00:50:01,433
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

940
00:50:01,476 --> 00:50:04,958
[RAINFALL]

941
00:50:21,235 --> 00:50:24,717
[CHATTER]

942
00:50:28,112 --> 00:50:29,548
Is Simon in his office?

943
00:50:29,591 --> 00:50:30,897
Uh, I didn't see him in there.

944
00:50:30,940 --> 00:50:31,767
Why?

945
00:50:31,811 --> 00:50:33,247
[CHATTER]

946
00:50:33,291 --> 00:50:36,772
[MUSIC PLAYING]

947
00:51:20,425 --> 00:51:21,382
[CAR DOOR SHUTS]

948
00:51:34,830 --> 00:51:35,788
[KNOCKING]

949
00:51:38,269 --> 00:51:39,270
[DOOR OPENS]

950
00:51:40,358 --> 00:51:41,272
Can I help you?

951
00:51:41,315 --> 00:51:42,751
Hi, Adele Cooke?

952
00:51:42,795 --> 00:51:44,797
Are you Melissa Rutherford's
next of kin?

953
00:51:44,840 --> 00:51:46,973
I'm her mother.

954
00:51:47,016 --> 00:51:48,453
I'm sorry for your loss, ma'am.

955
00:51:48,496 --> 00:51:51,064
Could I speak to you for a few
minutes?

956
00:51:51,108 --> 00:51:54,981
Yeah, come on in.

957
00:51:55,024 --> 00:52:07,646
[DOOR CLOSES]

958
00:52:07,689 --> 00:52:10,779
I work the obituaries desk at
"The Tribune."

959
00:52:10,823 --> 00:52:13,869
I wasn't aware "The Tribune"
was so thorough.

960
00:52:13,913 --> 00:52:15,697
Actually, I'm not here
officially.

961
00:52:15,741 --> 00:52:18,961
I just need to clear up a few
things for myself.

962
00:52:19,005 --> 00:52:20,354
Do you have a picture of
Melissa?

963
00:52:20,398 --> 00:52:21,877
Mhm, yes, right there.

964
00:52:31,278 --> 00:52:32,192
[SWOOSH]

965
00:52:32,236 --> 00:52:35,630
[LAUGHTER]

966
00:52:36,240 --> 00:52:37,110
[SWOOSH]

967
00:52:37,154 --> 00:52:40,200
Miss Wilcox, are you all right?

968
00:52:40,244 --> 00:52:42,724
Did Melissa ever work at a
Cliffcrest Hospital?

969
00:52:42,768 --> 00:52:44,204
Why, yes.

970
00:52:44,248 --> 00:52:46,293
Until they shut it down.

971
00:52:46,337 --> 00:52:47,686
But she wasn't Rutherford.

972
00:52:47,729 --> 00:52:49,862
No, Cooke.

973
00:52:49,905 --> 00:52:52,256
She took the name of Rutherford
when she got married.

974
00:52:52,299 --> 00:52:53,605
It only lasted a little while.

975
00:52:53,648 --> 00:52:54,954
But she kept the name.

976
00:52:54,997 --> 00:52:57,348
She liked the sound of it.

977
00:52:57,391 --> 00:53:01,395
And everyone always called her
Millie, not Melissa.

978
00:53:01,439 --> 00:53:02,309
I knew her.

979
00:53:05,269 --> 00:53:07,923
She saved my life.

980
00:53:07,967 --> 00:53:09,490
You were a patient?

981
00:53:09,534 --> 00:53:12,319
[MUSIC PLAYING]

982
00:53:12,363 --> 00:53:15,453
Millie was the only one who
ever cared about me.

983
00:53:15,496 --> 00:53:17,803
She didn't think of me as a
crazy kid,

984
00:53:17,846 --> 00:53:20,371
but somebody to help.

985
00:53:23,591 --> 00:53:24,897
She was wonderful.

986
00:53:28,335 --> 00:53:30,294
Yeah.

987
00:53:30,337 --> 00:53:31,251
She was.

988
00:53:36,735 --> 00:53:37,562
[SOBBING]

989
00:53:37,605 --> 00:53:38,606
She was.

990
00:53:44,003 --> 00:53:45,309
DETECTIVE WALKER: What do you
got, Moody?

991
00:53:45,352 --> 00:53:46,745
OFFICER MOODY [ON RADIO]: Denise
Wilcox was

992
00:53:46,788 --> 00:53:48,442
in Cliffcrest for over a year.

993
00:53:48,486 --> 00:53:50,401
Nervous breakdown-- I couldn't
get any more

994
00:53:50,444 --> 00:53:51,706
than that without a warrant.

995
00:53:51,750 --> 00:53:53,578
DETECTIVE WALKER: I'll get that
process started.

996
00:53:53,621 --> 00:53:55,144
OFFICER MOODY: I found out
something else this afternoon.

997
00:53:55,188 --> 00:53:56,450
What do you got?

998
00:53:56,494 --> 00:53:57,756
Before she went to Cliffcrest,
she was an honor

999
00:53:57,799 --> 00:53:59,801
student, top of her class.

1000
00:53:59,845 --> 00:54:01,499
And guess who her boyfriend was?

1001
00:54:01,542 --> 00:54:02,413
Who?

1002
00:54:02,456 --> 00:54:03,979
OFFICER MOODY: Simon Castillo.

1003
00:54:04,023 --> 00:54:05,285
Interesting.

1004
00:54:05,329 --> 00:54:07,244
They worked together on the
high school paper.

1005
00:54:07,287 --> 00:54:09,376
So her ex-boyfriend gets the
job she feels

1006
00:54:09,420 --> 00:54:10,856
rightfully belongs to her.

1007
00:54:10,899 --> 00:54:13,337
But she's got to take a little
vacation at Cliffcrest.

1008
00:54:13,380 --> 00:54:14,425
Not a bad motive.

1009
00:54:14,468 --> 00:54:15,774
But murderer?

1010
00:54:15,817 --> 00:54:18,255
I mean, sure, she's a bit of a
whack job, but--

1011
00:54:18,298 --> 00:54:19,299
Come on, Moody.

1012
00:54:19,343 --> 00:54:20,387
Please.

1013
00:54:20,431 --> 00:54:22,215
She's driven, looking for a
break.

1014
00:54:22,259 --> 00:54:24,173
She's angry at the newspaper
because he mistreated her.

1015
00:54:24,217 --> 00:54:25,479
Put that together with the fact
that she

1016
00:54:25,523 --> 00:54:27,438
is a bit of a whack job.

1017
00:54:27,481 --> 00:54:30,092
Who knows what she might do?

1018
00:54:30,136 --> 00:54:31,050
[PHONE RINGING]

1019
00:54:31,093 --> 00:54:34,009
[CHATTER]

1020
00:54:34,053 --> 00:54:39,101
Luke, did Simon take the
picture at Ramsey park?

1021
00:54:39,145 --> 00:54:40,015
What picture?

1022
00:54:40,059 --> 00:54:41,887
The one with the clown.

1023
00:54:41,930 --> 00:54:42,975
I guess.

1024
00:54:43,018 --> 00:54:44,629
Roger asked Simon to check me
out.

1025
00:54:44,672 --> 00:54:46,021
Why?

1026
00:54:46,065 --> 00:54:48,937
Actually, I think it was the
other way around.

1027
00:54:48,981 --> 00:54:50,243
What?

1028
00:54:50,287 --> 00:54:52,332
Luke, someone is messing with
me.

1029
00:54:52,376 --> 00:54:53,899
And I want to know who and why.

1030
00:54:53,942 --> 00:54:55,292
You said if you heard anything--

1031
00:54:55,335 --> 00:54:57,990
All I know is that Simon said
you

1032
00:54:58,033 --> 00:55:00,079
had an overactive imagination
and that you've

1033
00:55:00,122 --> 00:55:01,167
been acting strange.

1034
00:55:05,737 --> 00:55:08,827
Hey, don't do anything you'll
regret.

1035
00:55:08,870 --> 00:55:10,742
[PHONE RINGING]

1036
00:55:10,785 --> 00:55:14,180
[CHATTER]

1037
00:55:15,181 --> 00:55:16,878
There was a picture of Kali on
the wall.

1038
00:55:16,922 --> 00:55:18,184
I know what I saw. [SIGH]

1039
00:55:18,227 --> 00:55:19,098
Look, can you sit down?

1040
00:55:19,141 --> 00:55:20,012
Let's talk.

1041
00:55:20,055 --> 00:55:21,143
Did you paint over it?

1042
00:55:21,187 --> 00:55:22,275
Why would I do something like
that?

1043
00:55:22,319 --> 00:55:23,711
To discredit me.

1044
00:55:23,755 --> 00:55:25,104
I mean, that's why you've been
following me around,

1045
00:55:25,147 --> 00:55:27,193
why you asked Roger if you could
check out my theory.

1046
00:55:27,236 --> 00:55:28,237
Look, that's not true, Denise.

1047
00:55:28,281 --> 00:55:29,326
I was trying to help.

1048
00:55:29,369 --> 00:55:30,936
You were afraid that I would
find

1049
00:55:30,979 --> 00:55:32,938
something out and get a story
and leave you out in the cold.

1050
00:55:32,981 --> 00:55:34,069
Come on, Denise. That's crazy.

1051
00:55:34,113 --> 00:55:35,680
[PHONE RINGING]

1052
00:55:35,723 --> 00:55:37,029
Hey, it's Simon.

1053
00:55:37,072 --> 00:55:38,335
Look, I'll call you back, Mom.

1054
00:55:38,378 --> 00:55:41,468
Uncle Roger-- I'll tell him to
give you a call.

1055
00:55:41,512 --> 00:55:42,382
[HANGS UP]

1056
00:55:42,426 --> 00:55:43,296
[SIGH]

1057
00:55:43,340 --> 00:55:44,819
Roger is your uncle?

1058
00:55:44,863 --> 00:55:46,299
Look, Denise--

1059
00:55:46,343 --> 00:55:48,954
Oh, all that crap about Simon
being highly qualified,

1060
00:55:48,997 --> 00:55:50,347
how he went straight to college.

1061
00:55:53,393 --> 00:55:55,743
You knew I was at "The Tribune"
all along.

1062
00:55:55,787 --> 00:55:57,179
[STAMMERING]

1063
00:55:58,137 --> 00:55:59,399
Come on, Denise.

1064
00:55:59,443 --> 00:56:00,313
